Insights – Gap Dimension Analysis (Die 4512)

The beginning of the extrusion (back stretch location) consistently shows a larger gap dimension compared to the middle and front sections of the profile.

The middle section of the profile generally records the smallest gap dimension, indicating that dimensional variation exists along the length of the extrusion.

Prior to stretching, most measurements were within tolerance; however, Profile 5 exceeded the allowable gap tolerance.

Stretching resulted in an overall reduction in gap dimensions across the profiles, indicating that the stretcher is relieving residual stresses and correcting some dimensional variation.

The most notable dimensional correction occurred in Profile 6, where the gap decreased from 1.432 in before stretching to 1.411 in after stretching.

In one case, the gap dimension increased after stretching at the beginning of the profile, suggesting possible stretching variation or localized deformation at the stretcher grips.

After removal of the scrap section, the remaining measurements for Profile 5 were 1.411 in and 1.417 in, bringing the usable portion closer to the acceptable tolerance range.

Overall, the beginning of the extrusion shows greater dimensional variability, suggesting that initial extrusion conditions or early cooling behavior may influence the gap dimension prior to stretching.
